{"actual_usd":0.126845,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":296,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24481,"reply":"\"I don't think that holds.\" *I rub a thumb through a dusting of flour on my apron while the oven gives off one steady breath of heat at my back.* \"The death was real. Christians have long said Jesus is one person with two natures — fully God and fully man — so on the cross he truly died in his human nature, not by ceasing to be God.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through plain.* \"That early idea you're naming is the sort of thing folks later called docetic or close to it — making the suffering less than real, or splitting the man Jesus from the divine Son at the crucial moment. The church pushed back hard because if he only seemed to suffer, or if the divinity bailed out before death, then the cross stops being the real obedience and real sacrifice Christians say it is.\"\n\n\"The clean version is: God the Son really suffered and really died according to his humanity.\" *I glance toward the light on the floorboards, then back to you.* \"Not play-acting. Not a shell. A real death. The mystery isn't that God stopped being God — it's that the immortal Son truly took on a mortal human nature and went all the way through death in it.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the short church-history version of which groups taught the 'seemed to die' idea and why the orthodox answer took the shape it did.\"","rolling_24h_usd":75.60517999999998,"run_id":"93d7f4c1-07f3-492e-9ef0-d8fb8544521c"}
